Burning holes in pistons is a common problem with 2 cycle engines. For this reason the builders of the engine, Fuji Heavy In'd, do not warrant against this problem.  When a problem like this occurs Neoteric has to decide the cause of the problem where possible. The causes can be many but mostly it is the result of insufficient fuel supply. This causes the engine to run lean. The condition which preceeds melting. Insufficient fuel flow can result from a restriction anywhere in the fuel system.  For example a blocked fuel filter,  debree in the gas tank, a defective primer bulb, a blockage in the fuel pump or any one of the fuel lines.   Other conditions will also lead to this failure. Not following the breakin procedure outlined in the manual. The use of oil other than what is recommended in the manual. When an engine is new it is tight and the rings have not seated properly. Consequently they cannot effectively transmit heat from the piston into the cylinder. The piston overheats and melts. Checking the color of the spark plug after 1 hour and after 3 hr then at 5hr is a good idea. Also, while the engine is running watch the cylinder head temp specially  during the low hours of engine life.  If grass is allowed to collect around the cylinder this also promotes cylinder overheating and subsequent failure. We agree to pay you compensation as an act of goodwill. Because Fuji does not accept  responsibility for this type of failure nor should Neoteric. Our standard cost for replacing a piston is $110. If you will kindly send an invoice for this amount I will issue a check. We will also provide the following components and honing service without any cost to you. It is advised that you fit the 270 jets provided and set the clip ring on the needle valve one notch lower. Both these suggestions are intended to help derate the engine performance slightly and to reduce engine operating temperature.  Follow the breakin procedure outlined in the manual.

I have setup a test apparatus and checked intake manifold for air leaks. At about 20psi I could see no sign of any leakage. Larger jets were fitted and the needle jet was  opened to the next notch. Both these changes could slightly depower the engine but should help to lower cylinder temperature.  No evidence of the cause of failure was found. In conclusion, the engine reached overheating range and the No1 piston failed. Possible causes could be a restriction in fuel system. The engine fuel system has been opened and completely inspected, and no blockages were found. A blockage in the fuel tank or the primer bulb still remain as possibilities. Any grass buildup around the cylinder would also cause this type of failure. Likewise insufficient oil. Oil should be 30:1 for the next six hours. Thereafter go to 40 to 1.Oil should be common quality name brand such as Valvoline, BP, Castrol, Quaker State etc. It is advised to use snowmobile oil where available. Fuel should be 82 octane and above. Lastly, pushing an engine too hard before it is run-in can also cause this type of failure. Piston melting is common on all  high performance 2 cycle engines. Because it can be caused by any of a number of possibilities, the engine manufacture, Fuji Heavy In'd, does not warrant against piston melting. If the engine manufacture is not prepared to warrant nor should Neoteric be responsible. We will however agree to assume the cost of this failure as an act of goodwill. We do not warrant the engine against this type of failure. To much depends on the owners operational style to be able to warrant against this type of failure. Check the plugs after the first hours operation and ensure yourself that both plugs are chocklet in color.
